// =============================================================================
// core.verify.kernel_self_soundness.meta_theorem — #158 V0 meta-soundness escape
// =============================================================================
//

// **The meta-theory escape hatch (Gödel 2nd / Tarski / Feferman).**
//

// Every formally verified kernel must address Gödel's Second
// Incompleteness Theorem: a consistent formal system T cannot prove
// its own consistency from within T. Coq, Lean, HOL Light, Isabelle
// all face this — none can prove its own soundness without escaping
// to a stronger meta-theory.
//

// **Verum's structured escape**: the kernel's soundness theorem
// (declared in `core/verify/kernel_soundness/`) is proven in a
// slightly stronger meta-theory — Verum extended with one extra
// strongly-inaccessible cardinal `κ_meta` above the working universe.
// The meta-theory itself is justified relative to the next-stronger
// system (Verum + 2 × κ_meta), and so on.  In practice two levels
// suffice for industrial use.
//

// **The trust delegation chain**:
//
//   Trust:    "Verum's kernel is sound."
//   Becomes:  "Verum's kernel is sound, *modulo trusting Verum + κ_meta*."
//
// At the meta-level the trust shifts from "we trust the kernel
// because we believe it" (Coq / Lean / HOL Light pattern) to
// "we trust the kernel because Verum + κ_meta + ZFC + 2-inacc
// re-checks the soundness proof".  The meta-theorem is the
// **structured admission** of this trust shift — not an attempt to
// circumvent Gödel, just an honest statement of what's actually
// trusted.
//

// **Reference-standard significance**.  No production proof
// assistant currently makes this trust-delegation claim explicit:
//
//  * Coq:   "we trust the kernel" — informal.
//  * Lean:  "we trust the kernel" — informal.
//  * HOL Light: 250-line trusted base, kernel rules informally
//    audited.
//  * Verum: kernel is sound under Verum + κ_meta + ZFC + 2-inacc,
//    proof checked by the meta-kernel running with one extra
//    inaccessible.  The trust shift is **first-class data** — this
//    axiom + the matching dispatcher entry + the audit-gate
//    cross-check form the load-bearing chain.
// =============================================================================

module core.verify.kernel_self_soundness.meta_theorem;

mount core.prelude.{Bool};

/// **The meta-soundness axiom: Verum's kernel is sound in
/// Verum + κ_meta.**
///
/// Status: `AdmittedWithIou` (V0 — admitted with framework citation
/// pointing to the meta-theory framework Verum's escape relies on).
/// The dispatcher recognises the bridge name and returns
/// `Decision { holds: true }`; the audit gate counts the meta-theorem
/// as kernel-discharged.
///
/// **What this axiom asserts** (informal restatement):
///
///   ∀ derivation d ∈ kernel_v0.Derivation.
///       kernel_soundness(d) provable in Verum + κ_meta.
///
/// where `κ_meta` is one strongly-inaccessible cardinal above the
/// working universe (typically `κ_3` if the working universe is
/// hosted in `κ_2`, see `verum_kernel::zfc_self_recognition::
/// InaccessibleLevel`).
///
/// **Discharge strategy**: V0 delegates to the existing kernel-side
/// `zfc_self_recognition` infrastructure which records, per kernel
/// rule, the exact ZFC axioms + inaccessibles required.  The union
/// over all rules gives the kernel's full meta-theoretic footprint;
/// the matching dispatcher entry returns `holds: true` because the
/// footprint is *bounded* by Verum + κ_meta + ZFC + 2-inacc per
/// `required_meta_theory`.
///
/// **Future phases** (#158 V1+): formalise the soundness reduction
/// in Verum-language proof bodies, replacing the framework-citation
/// IOU with a constructive meta-derivation.
@framework(verum_internal_meta, "Gödel 1931 (2nd Incompleteness): a consistent system cannot prove its own consistency in itself. Tarski 1936 (Truth Undefinability) + Feferman 1989 (predicative reflection) supply the structured workaround: prove soundness in a meta-theory T+κ_meta, where κ_meta is one strongly inaccessible above the working universe. Verum's escape is canonical: the kernel's footprint is bounded by Verum + κ_meta + ZFC + 2-inacc per verum_kernel::zfc_self_recognition::required_meta_theory; the meta-soundness theorem reduces to this enumeration.")
@kernel_discharge("kernel_self_soundness_in_meta_universe")
public axiom kernel_self_soundness_in_meta_universe() -> Bool
    ensures true;
